I think thing here is to realize that the keys of `martini.Params` are taken straight from the named capture groups of the regex. As @mvader pointed out, the full regex ends up looking something like `(?P<id>[^/#?]+)([0-9]+)`. That is, `:name` is syntactic sugar for "bind a single piece of a URL to the name `name`."

So to get the behavior you want, just introduce the named capture directly. Here's a full working example:

``` go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "log"

    "github.com/go-martini/martini"
)

func main() {
    m := martini.Classic()
    m.Get("/test/(?P<id>[0-9]+)", func(p martini.Params) string {
        return fmt.Sprintf("ID %s", p["id"])
    })
    m.Run()
}
```

Firstly, `martini` has a new import path: `github.com/go-martini/martini`.

Secondly, the logger is only enabled by default if you're using classic martini. If you want more fine grained control, then you can build your own custom martini. It's actually very easy. Take a look at the `ClassicMartini` function:

``` go
func Classic() *ClassicMartini {
    r := NewRouter()
    m := New()
    m.Use(Logger())
    m.Use(Recovery())
    m.Use(Static("public"))
    m.MapTo(r, (*Routes)(nil))
    m.Action(r.Handle)
    return &ClassicMartini{m, r}
}
```

So you can use that function, except omit the `m.Use(Logger())` line. Here's a full working example:

``` go
package main

import (
    "log"

    "github.com/go-martini/martini"
)

type myClassic struct {
    *martini.Martini
    martini.Router
}

func withoutLogging() *myClassic {
    r := martini.NewRouter()
    m := martini.New()
    m.Use(martini.Recovery())
    m.Use(martini.Static("public"))
    m.MapTo(r, (*martini.Routes)(nil))
    m.Action(r.Handle)
    return &myClassic{m, r}
}

func main() {
    m := withoutLogging()
    m.Get("/", func(lg *log.Logger) string {
        return "Hello, world!"
    })
    m.Run()
}
```

